qas.question: According to tradition, where did Virgil travel in 19 BC to revise the Aeneid?

answers.text: Lucius Varius Rufus and Plotius Tucca

qas.question: What wish of Virgil's did Lucius Varius Rufus and Plotius Tucca disregard?
What date was the Aeneid published?
Where was the Aeneid first published?
Exactly how many unfinished lines are in the Aeneid?

context: According to the tradition, Virgil traveled to <a0_0>Greece<a0_0/> in about <b9_0>19<b9_0/> BC to revise the Aeneid. After meeting Augustus in Athens and deciding to return home, Virgil caught <b7_0>a fever<b7_0/> while visiting a town near Megara. After crossing to <b8_0>Italy<b8_0/> by ship, weakened with disease, Virgil died in <a1_0><b5_0>Brundisium harbor<b5_0/><a1_0/> on <a2_0><b6_0>September 21, 19 BC<b6_0/><a2_0/>. Augustus ordered Virgil's literary executors, <a3_0>Lucius Varius Rufus and Plotius Tucca<a3_0/>, to disregard Virgil's own wish that <a4_0>the poem be burned<a4_0/>, instead ordering it published with as few editorial changes as possible. As a result, the text of the Aeneid that exists may contain faults which Virgil was planning to correct before publication. However, the only obvious imperfections are a few lines of verse that are metrically unfinished (i.e. not a complete line of dactylic hexameter). Some scholars have argued that Virgil deliberately left these metrically incomplete lines for dramatic effect. Other alleged imperfections are subject to scholarly debate.
